{"title_page": "Daron Malakian and Scars on Broadway", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n|name = Daron Malakian and Scars on Broadway\n|origin = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], US\n|genre = {{hlist|[[Alternative metal]]|[[experimental rock]]}}\n|image = DM-photo.jpg\n|caption = Band founder, vocalist and guitarist [[Daron Malakian]] in 2011\n|background = group_or_band\n|years_active = 2006\u20132009, 2010\u20132012, 2018\u2013present\n|label = [[Interscope Records|Interscope]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Scars on Broadway Signs with Interscope|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/scars-on-broadway-signs-with-interscope/|website=[[BlabberMouth.net]]|date=9 May 2008|accessdate=6 May 2018}}</ref>\n|associated_acts = [[System of a Down]], [[Amen (American band)|Amen]], [[Axis of Justice]], [[Viza]], The Chronicles of Israfel, [[Hella (band)|Hella]], [[Pulse Ultra]], [[Scum (band)|Scum]], [[Team Sleep]], [[DKFXP]]\n|website = {{URL|http://www.scarsonbroadway.com/}}\n|current_members = \n*[[Daron Malakian]]\n|past_members = Dominic Cifarelli<br>[[John Dolmayan]]<br>Jules Pampena<br>[[Franky Perez]]<br>Danny Shamoun\n}}\n\n'''Daron Malakian and Scars on Broadway''' (previously known as just '''Scars on Broadway''') is an American [[Rock music|rock]] band, founded by [[Daron Malakian]] of the metal band [[System of a Down]]. The band's [[Scars on Broadway (album)|eponymous debut album]] was released on July 29, 2008.\n\nIn late 2008, the band entered a hiatus, with Malakian citing a lack of enthusiasm and \"his heart not being into touring\", as the primary reasons for the band's cessation. Despite reforming with various line-up changes in 2010 and 2012, and announcing a second album, the band ceased any further announcements by 2013. In April 2018 Malakian announced that the band would be releasing their second album titled ''[[Dictator (album)|Dictator]]'' on July 20, 2018.\n\n==History==\n===Self-titled debut album (2005\u20132008)===\nIn December 2005, Malakian stated in an interview that he \"could release ten solo records tomorrow.\"<ref name=\"Solo0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/interviews/soads_daron_malakian_i_could_release_ten_solo_records_tomorrow.html|title=SOAD's Daron Malakian: 'I Could Release Ten Solo Records Tomorrow'|website=Ultimate-guitar.com|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> He revealed that he has \"tons of material laying around\", as well as his plans for the future: \"After these albums, \u2013 (''[[Mezmerize (album)|Mezmerize]]'' and ''[[Hypnotize (album)|Hypnotize]]'') \u2013 I'm gonna go off and do something on my own, just like [[Serj Tankian|Serj]].\"<ref name=\"Solo0\"/> Following System of a Down's hiatus in May 2006, Malakian announced his latest project&nbsp;\u2014 Scars on Broadway&nbsp;\u2014 a band which would include System of a Down drummer [[John Dolmayan]] and himself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1530066/system-of-a-down-arent-breaking-up-theyre-going-on-hiatus/|title=System Of A Down Aren't Breaking Up &#8212; They're Going On Hiatus|website=Mtv.com|accessdate=15 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gigwise.com/features/44377/covering-up-old-wounds-scars-on-broadway|title=Covering Up Old Wounds: Scars On Broadway|website=Gigwise.com|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"RS\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/in-the-studio-system-of-a-down-side-project-scars-on-broadway-trades-metal-for-melodic-rock-20080128|title=In the Studio: System of a Down Side Project Scars on Broadway Trades Metal for Melodic Rock|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> Malakian stated \"I haven't decided if I'm going to make it a revolving door of musicians or one solid band but it all revolves around my writing.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gigwise.com/news/12648/system-of-a-downs-daron-malakian-goes-solo|title=System Of A Down's Daron Malakian Goes Solo|website=Gigwise.com|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter Malakian and Dolmayan experimented with different musicians, for a period of nine months in 2007 the band took form and forged its sound in intense rehearsals and recording sessions under Malakian's direction at his home studio and Sunset Sound; with musicians Danny Shamoun on keyboards, Dominic Cifarelli on bass, and [[Franky Perez]] on guitar and backing vocals. The band begin recording their debut album in September 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/system-of-a-down-members-recording-18-songs-for-scars-on-broadway-debut/|title=SYSTEM OF A DOWN Members Recording 18 Songs For SCARS ON BROADWAY Debut|date=29 September 2007|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe band's website featured a countdown timer, counting down to 15:00 PST on March 28, 2008. Additionally, above the timer, in quotation marks was the phrase \"They say it's all about to end.\" When the countdown ended, the song \"[[They Say]]\" was made available on the site and their [[Myspace]] account.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/system-of-a-down-guitarist-s-scars-on-broadway-releases-first-track/|title=SYSTEM OF A DOWN Guitarist's SCARS ON BROADWAY Releases First Track|date=28 March 2008|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nScars on Broadway played their first live show April 11, 2008, at the Whisky A Go Go in Los Angeles, CA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/system-of-a-down-guitarist-s-scars-on-broadway-to-play-hollywood-tonight/|title=SYSTEM OF A DOWN Guitarist's SCARS ON BROADWAY To Play Hollywood Tonight|date=11 April 2008|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> They also played with [[Metallica]] at KFMA Day 2008 in Tucson, AZ.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/metallica-confirmed-for-kfma-day-in-tucson/|title=METALLICA Confirmed For KFMA DAY In Tucson|date=31 March 2008|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> On January 22, 2008, Scars on Broadway were announced to be performing at the [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival]] on April 26, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pe.com/2008/04/21/more-with-coachella-act-scars-on-broadway/|title=More with Coachella act Scars on Broadway|date=21 April 2008|website=Pe.com|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> They also performed at the sixteenth annual [[KROQ-FM|KROQ]] [[KROQ Weenie Roast|Weenie Roast]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1045632/metallica-the-offspring-lead-weenie-roast-lineup|title=Metallica, The Offspring Lead Weenie Roast Lineup|website=Billboard.com|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn May 2, 2008, the band announced that their debut album, ''[[Scars on Broadway (album)|Scars on Broadway]]'', would be released on July 28, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/scars-on-broadway-sets-release-date-for-debut-album/|title=SCARS ON BROADWAY Sets Release Date For Debut Album|date=2 May 2008|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/scars-on-broadway-1334362|title=System Of A Down members launches new band \u2013 NME|date=30 May 2008|website=Nme.com|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> A week later, the band was signed to [[Interscope Records]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/scars-on-broadway-signs-with-interscope/|title=SCARS ON BROADWAY Signs With INTERSCOPE|date=9 May 2008|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> The first single would be the aforementioned \"They Say\", which would receive radio airplay, and be made available on ''[[Guitar Hero 5]]'' and as a downloadable track on ''[[Rock Band]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2009/07/08/unofficial-the-complete-guitar-hero-5-track-list/|title=The complete Guitar Hero 5 track list|website=Engadget.com|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/staind-scars-on-broadway-testament-part-of-rock-band-download-catalog/|title=STAIND, SCARS ON BROADWAY, TESTAMENT Part Of 'Rock Band' Download Catalog|date=25 July 2008|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/scars-on-broadway-s-daron-malakian-has-his-say/|title=SCARS ON BROADWAY's DARON MALAKIAN Has His 'Say'|date=27 May 2008|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> The music video for the track was released on June 27.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/scars-on-broadway-they-say-video-available/|title=SCARS ON BROADWAY: 'They Say' Video Available|date=27 June 2008|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref>\n[[file:JohnDolmayanSitting.jpg|thumb|Former drummer [[John Dolmayan]]]]\n\nIn July, the band announced a headlining tour set for October 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/scars-on-broadway-to-embark-on-north-american-tour-in-october/|title=SCARS ON BROADWAY To Embark On North American Tour In October|date=25 June 2008|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> ''Scars on Broadway'' was released on July 28, 2008, to generally favorable reviews and debuted at No. 17 on the [[Billboard 200|Billboard charts]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/scars-on-broadway-s-debut-lands-in-billboard-s-top/|title=SCARS ON BROADWAY's Debut Lands In Billboard's Top 20|date=6 August 2008|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/scars-on-broadway/scars-on-broadway|title=Scars On Broadway by Scars On Broadway|website=[[Metacritic.com]]|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> A second single, \"World Long Gone\", was released on September 8, and featured a music video directed by filmmaker [[Joel Schumacher]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/scars-on-broadway-world-long-gone-video-posted-online/|title=SCARS ON BROADWAY: 'World Long Gone' Video Posted Online|date=9 September 2008|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/scars-on-broadway-taps-joel-schumacher-for-world-long-gone-video-shoot/|title=SCARS ON BROADWAY Taps JOEL SCHUMACHER For 'World Long Gone' Video Shoot|date=19 August 2008|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Hiatus, reformation, and second hiatus (2008\u20132018)===\nIn late 2008, Malakian announced that the headlining tour to promote the album's release, which included an appearance on [[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]], would be cancelled with no plans of rescheduling.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/scars-on-broadway-3-1331205|title=Scars On Broadway cancel US tour \u2013 NME|date=10 October 2008|website=Nme.com|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> Malakian cited personal reasons as the reason behind the cancellations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/scars-on-broadway-s-daron-malakian-has-compelling-reasons-for-cancelling-tour/|title=SCARS ON BROADWAY's DARON MALAKIAN Has 'Compelling Reasons' For Cancelling Tour|date=9 October 2008|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> Malakian later cited burn-out of touring as an additional factor behind the cancellations. Interviews with both Cifarelli and Dolmayan suggested that the band was finished.<ref>{{cite web|title=Scars' bassist says, Scars on Broadway is pretty much over|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091230154632/http://www.soadfans.com/Article665.htm|website=SOADFans.com|accessdate=28 November 2014|url=http://www.soadfans.com/Article665.htm|archivedate=December 30, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soadfans.com/PNphpBB2-viewtopic-t-25429-postdays-0-postorder-asc.htm|title=I smoked Shavo out! a.k.a. My experience at Greg W's Gallery :: The Official UnOfficial System Of a Down Site!|date=30 December 2009|website=Soadfans.com|accessdate=24 April 2018|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091230153101/http://www.soadfans.com/PNphpBB2-viewtopic-t-25429-postdays-0-postorder-asc.htm|archivedate=30 December 2009}}</ref> When asked later in May 2009 if the band would ever record or perform again, drummer John Dolmayan stated: \"I'm not sure, but I do miss it.\"<ref>{{cite web | author=Lindsay, Andrew | title=Interview: John Dolmayan (System of a Down/Scars on Broadway) | date=2009-05-17 | url=http://stereokill.net/2009/05/17/interview-john-dolmayan-system-of-a-down-scars-on-broadway/ | website=Stereokill.net | accessdate=2009-05-17 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120723101910/http://stereokill.net/2009/05/17/interview-john-dolmayan-system-of-a-down-scars-on-broadway/ | archivedate=2012-07-23 }}</ref>\n\nIn August 2009, Dolmayan, Perez, Shamoun, and Cifarelli as Scars on Broadway traveled to [[Iraq]] for a USO tour across the US army bases, without Malakian.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artisannews.com/scars-on-broadway-on-hiatus-or-broken-up/|title=SCARS ON BROADWAY ON HIATUS OR BROKEN UP|date=18 January 2010|website=Artisannews.com|accessdate=24 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180425114827/http://www.artisannews.com/scars-on-broadway-on-hiatus-or-broken-up/|archive-date=25 April 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/scars-on-broadway-members-touring-army-bases-in-iraq/|title=SCARS ON BROADWAY Members Touring Army Bases In Iraq|date=24 August 2009|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> Their setlist consisted of covers as well as a few Scars on Broadway songs. Perez stated on his [[Twitter]] that \"the Scars tunes sound amazing but they're not the same without D...\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Twitter Post|last=Perez|first=Franky|url=https://twitter.com/FrankyPerez/status/3281864538|publisher=Twitter|accessdate=16 October 2014}}</ref> On October 31, 2009, Malakian performed with Perez, Dolmayan, and System of a Down bassist Shavo Odadjian for Odadjian's Halloween party at [[Roxie Theater]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/system-of-a-down-members-reunite-for-halloween-performance/|title=SYSTEM OF A DOWN Members Reunite For Halloween Performance|date=2 November 2009|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> The group performed a System of a Down song (\"Suite-Pee\"), a Scars on Broadway song (\"They Say\") as well as an untitled song.\n\nOn April 10, 2010, the band announced their return show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/scars-on-broadway-announces-comeback-show/|title=SCARS ON BROADWAY Announces Comeback Show|date=13 April 2010|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> On May 2, Scars on Broadway played a sold out show at The Troubadour in West Hollywood.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/scars-on-broadway-returns-to-live-stage-after-17-month-absence-video-available/|title=SCARS ON BROADWAY Returns To Live Stage After 17-Month Absence; Video Available|date=3 May 2010|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> The band performed all of the songs off their first album (except for \"Kill Each Other / Live Forever\"), as well as a new song \"Talkin' Shit\". They also played a cover song \"Forever My Queen\" by the band [[Pentagram (band)|Pentagram]]. System of a Down bassist Shavo Odadjian accompanied and played 3rd guitar for \"Cute Machines\" and \"They Say\".\n\nOn July 29, 2010, a new song titled \"Fucking\" was released on [[SoundCloud]], using a special feature where users had to share the song on social media to unlock the download.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/scars-on-broadway-new-song-available-for-free-download/|title=SCARS ON BROADWAY: New Song Available For Free Download|date=29 July 2010|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> On August 20, 2010, Scars on Broadway played a sold out show at the Avalon in Hollywood.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theprp.com/2010/08/25/news/scars-on-broadway-play-new-tracks-cover-skinny-puppy-in-hollywood-ca-footage-of-entire-set-available/|title=Scars On Broadway Play New Tracks, Cover Skinny Puppy In Hollywood, CA, Footage Of Entire Set Available |website=Theprp.com|date=25 August 2010|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> The first 500 people in line at the concert received a free copy of the single on vinyl.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/scars-on-broadway-first-500-people-in-line-for-avalon-show-to-receive-free-single/|title=SCARS ON BROADWAY: First 500 People In Line For Avalon Show To Receive Free Single|date=19 August 2010|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> A music video for \"Fucking\" was later released in March 2011, using footage from the concert.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/scars-on-broadway-f-king-video-released/|title=SCARS ON BROADWAY: 'F**king' Video Released|date=14 March 2011|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2012 a preview of a new song called \"Guns Are Loaded\" was released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/scars-on-broadway-tease-new-song-guns-are-loaded/|title=Scars on Broadway Tease New Song \u2018Guns Are Loaded\u2019|website=Loudwire.com|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> In August, Dolmayan announced his departure, but stated the album was still scheduled for release \"in the next 3 to 4 months\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://puregrainaudio.com/interviews/interview-with-system-of-a-down-drummer-john-dolmayan|title=Interview with System Of A Down drummer John Dolmayan|first=Mitch|last=Lafon|website=Puregrainaudio.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/system-of-a-down-drummer-john-dolmayan-exits-scars-on-broadway/|title=System of a Down Drummer John Dolmayan Exits Scars on Broadway|website=Loudwire.com|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> In September 2012, an accompanying EP was announced to come out around the release of their second album as well. The band also performed at the Epicenter Festival in Irvine, Ca. with new drummer Jules Pampena.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitaldiversion.net/2012/10/scars-on-broadway-october-10-2012/|title=Scars On Broadway \u2013 October 10, 2012|website=Digitaldiversion.net|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/new-scars-on-broadway-lineup-performs-live-for-first-time-video/|title=New SCARS ON BROADWAY Lineup Performs Live For First Time (Video)|date=28 September 2012|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> However, Perez was not present, and later confirmed he had left the band as well.<ref>{{cite web|title=Facebook Wall Post|last=Perez|first=Franky|url=https://www.facebook.com/FrankyPerezOfficial/posts/10151227361780056|publisher=Facebook|accessdate=27 September 2012}}</ref> Malakian later talked about the upcoming album in November 2012, mentioning new songs \"Dictator\", \"Till the End\", and \"Fuck n Kill\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/system-of-a-down-guitarist-talks-new-scars-on-broadway-album/|title=SYSTEM OF A DOWN Guitarist Talks New SCARS ON BROADWAY Album|date=14 November 2012|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> Malakian also noted he will perform the entirety of the new album by himself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/system-of-a-down-daron-malakian-recording-new-scars-on-broadway-album-by-himself/|title=System of a Down\u2019s Daron Malakian Recording New Scars on Broadway Album by Himself|website=Loudwire.com|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nDespite plans for an untitled album to be out early 2013 mentioned at live shows, no new information regarding the album was given until 2018.\n\n===''Dictator'' (2018\u2013present)===\n{{Main|Dictator (album)}}\nOn April 16, 2018, Malakian announced the lead single from the second album would be released on April 23.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/system-of-a-down-guitarist-to-release-new-video-single-from-scars-on-broadway-project/|title=SYSTEM OF A DOWN Guitarist To Release New Video, Single From SCARS ON BROADWAY Project|date=16 April 2018|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> The band was re-branded as \u201cDaron Malakian and Scars on Broadway\u201d.<ref name=\"rs18\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/system-of-a-down-guitarist-on-new-solo-music-w519377|title=System of a Down Guitarist Talks First Solo Music in Eight Years|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> Regarding the change, Malakian stated, \"Nobody quit [the band]. When I first started Scars, I always said that it would be different line-ups from album to album. Depends on the type of direction I want to take. Different musicians work for different styles. That is partly why I added my name in front of the band's.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kerrang.com/the-news/system-of-a-downs-daron-malakian-to-release-new-scars-on-broadway-album/|title=System Of A Down\u2019s Daron Malakian To Release New Scars On Broadway Album \u2014 Kerrang!|website=Kerrang!|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> On April 23, 2018, Malakian released the official video of the song \"Lives\", also releasing the release date of the band's second album, titled ''Dictator'', on July 20, 2018.<ref name=\"rs18\"/> The song is meant to commemorate the [[Armenian Genocide]] and celebrate its survivors.<ref name=\"rs18\"/> The \"Lives\" music video featured guitarist Orbel Babayan, bassist Niko Chantziantoniou, and drummer Roman Lomtadze, who later joined the band as touring members.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kalepanagos |first1=Panos |title=DARON MALAKIAN AND SCARS ON BROADWAY: \"Lives\" (new video clip) |url=https://www.metalhammer.gr/hammer-tv/item/34177-daron-malakian-and-scars-on-broadway-lives-video |website=[[Metal Hammer]] |accessdate=11 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe album was recorded in 2012, with Malakian explaining the delay by saying \"Not knowing what's happening with System has kept me from putting my own stuff out. Too much time has passed, and I'm really excited to finally get some music out finally.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/system-of-a-downs-daron-malakian-releases-lives-single-from-scars-on-broadway-project/|title=SYSTEM OF A DOWN's DARON MALAKIAN Releases 'Lives' Single, Video From SCARS ON BROADWAY Project|date=23 April 2018|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> Malakian stated that the new album could have been System of a Down music, however members of the band couldn't agree on musical direction.<ref name=\"soad\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metalinjection.net/latest-news/bummer-alert/daron-malakian-says-scars-on-broadways-new-album-could-have-been-new-system-of-a-down-music|title=Daron Malakian Says SCARS ON BROADWAY's New Album Could Have Been New SYSTEM OF A DOWN Music|date=24 April 2018|website=Metalinjection.net|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> Malakian also confirmed that \"Gie mou\", a song originally sung by [[Stamatis Kokotas]], was going to be in the album.<ref name=\"Gie mou\">{{cite web|url=http://roxx.gr/2018/04/25/vomva-apo-ton-daron-malakian-sto-roxx-diaskevi-sto-gie-mou-tou-kokkota-sto-neo-almpoum-ton-scars-brodway/|title=Daron Malakian on Roxx.gr: \"Gie mou\" cover will be on dictator|date=25 April 2018|website=Roxx.gr|accessdate=25 April 2018}}</ref> Additionally, he revealed that he was working with a full band for the band's third release, scheduled to begin recording in August.<ref name=\"soad\"/>\n\n==Musical style==\nFrom its early days, [[Daron Malakian]] always addressed the project as just [[Rock music|rock]], and \"a lot more rock driven, although there will be some [[Heavy metal music|metal]] influences in the System of a Down style\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/music-scars-dc/soad-duo-in-final-stages-of-scars-on-broadway-album-idUSN0422169120080504|title=SOAD duo in|first=Mitchell|last=Peters|website=Reuters.com|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> Malakian stated, \"I think a System fan will be able to relate to the music, but there's a few different directions I want to take, whether it be a little bit more ethnic or sometimes electronic.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/system-of-a-down-guitarist-preps-new-band/|title=SYSTEM OF A DOWN Guitarist Preps New Band|date=8 June 2006|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> In a later interview, Malakian stated that the music would be influenced by [[classic rock]] acts such as [[David Bowie]], [[Brian Eno]], [[Neil Young]], and [[Roxy Music]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-et-scars28-2008jul28-story.html|title=Scars on Broadway's Daron Malakian takes a read of the times|first=By Richard|last=Cromelin|website=Latimes.com|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> He also stated that he shifted his songwriting from System of a Down's \"frazzled metal\" to more song-based work, which was inspired by Neil Young and David Bowie.<ref name=\"RS\"/> \"I don't feel we're the mosh-pit band,\" said Malakian. \"That's just where I'm comfortable as a writer right now,\" he said, hinting at the band's [[rock music|rock]] over metal music approach.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/jul/23/scars.on.broadway|title=No 355: Scars on Broadway|first=Paul|last=Lester|date=23 July 2008|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> He also stated his intentions for the band to \"have their own identity\" from System of a Down, while still maintaining the same \"thematic and sonic territory\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/system-of-a-down-guitarist-wants-scars-on-broadway-to-have-its-own-identity/|title=SYSTEM OF A DOWN Guitarist Wants SCARS ON BROADWAY To 'Have Its Own Identity'|date=15 January 2008|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Band members==\n===Current===\n* [[Daron Malakian]] \u2014 lead vocals, lead guitar, bass, keyboards, <small>(2006\u20132008, 2010-present)</small> drums <small>(2012\u2013present)</small>\n\n===Touring members===\n* Orbel Babayan - rhythm guitar, backing vocals, sampler <small>(2018-present)</small>\n* Niko Chantziantoniou - bass <small>(2018-present)</small>\n* Roman Lomtadze - drums <small>(2018-present)</small> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/community_feed/daron_malakian_and_scars_on_broadway_played_their_whole_repertoire_on_a_come-back_show_in_la.html|title=Daron Malakian and Scars On Broadway played their whole repertoire on a come-back show in LA|website=Ultimate-guitar.com}}</ref>\n===Former===\n\n* [[John Dolmayan]] \u2014 drums  <small>(2006\u20132009, 2010\u20132012)</small>\n* [[Franky Perez]] \u2014 rhythm guitar, backing vocals <small>(2008\u20132009, 2010)</small>\n* Danny Shamoun \u2014 keyboards, piano, percussion <small>(2008\u20132009, 2010\u20132012)</small>\n\n===Former touring members===\n* Dominic Cifarelli \u2014 bass, backing vocals <small>(The Chronicles of Israfel, ex-[[Pulse Ultra]]) (2008\u20132009, 2010\u20132012)</small>\n* Jules Pampena \u2014 drums <small>(2012)</small>\n\n==Timeline==\n<timeline>\nImageSize = width:800 height:300\nPlotArea = left:110 bottom:120 top:10 right:05\nAlignbars = justify\nDateFormat  = dd/mm/yyyy\nPeriod = from:01/01/2006 till:01/01/2020\nTimeAxis = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy\nLegend = orientation:vertical position:bottom columns:3\nScaleMajor = increment:2 start:2006\nScaleMinor = increment:1 start:2007\n\nColors =\n  id:LV        value:red         legend:Lead_vocals,_lead_guitar\n  id:BV        value:pink        legend:Backing_vocals\n  id:RG        value:green       legend:Rhythm_guitar\n  id:B         value:blue        legend:Bass\n  id:D         value:orange      legend:Drums\n  id:P         value:claret      lege